The South African bond market perked up a little on Tuesday morning, reflecting an improvement in the rand over the past 24 hours. Bond holders tend to benefit from the stronger rand, which helps keep inflation at bay. Statistics SA will on Wednesday release the updated inflation figures, along with retail sales for October. Trading Economics expects consumer inflation to have accelerated to 6.5% in November on an annualised basis, from 6.4% in October. The yield on the benchmark R186 bond was at 8.895% in early trade, from 8.900 on Monday The yield on the 10-year US treasury note flattened to 2.4886%, after crossing 2.50% on Monday for the first time since 2014, boosting the dollar. The price of Brent crude also pulled back from its multimonth highs of about $57 a barrel to allay inflation concerns.